1.body: This book aims to provide a brief overview of the how data analysis can be performed using modern tools that have only recently become available. These tools will primarily be free and open source software developed to help the community by numerous contributors. There will also be a focus on producing Web based publications to facilitate dissemination of report contents.

62.body: This book was produced with mdbook a command line tool static site generator that produces a book like format from Markdown files. Alternatives to mdbook would be static site generators like Hugo or Jekyll however these are more aimed at blog formats and while flexible enough to produce online books both seem to require more configuration. It can be installed and ran on most major operating systems(OS) from a binary file or a locally compiled copy, although some of the third party plugins only seem to work on a linux OS. Some, for example adding a quiz have other dependencies. By default mdbook also includes a number of features like search and print which can be omitted by editing the book.toml file in the book's root directory. Unfortunately, the print option only prints the full book, so has been disabled in this book. The book.toml file can also be used to set Preprocessors to customise the Markdown rendering. An number of these are included by default to allow latex to compile and also mdbook pulls in text files inclosed in double curly brackets like so John Halsall. It also uses colon notation to control the file line numbers used for example the following uses only the first two lines of the file Halsall The book was mainly edited using VScode with Extension for Markdown, HTML, Javascript and toml. As mdbook uses text files it is possible to create elements with a scripting language and paste links into the SUMMARY.md file to automate the creation of the book from preexisting files. There is also a jinja2 like extensible templating engine though a rust Tera preprocessor. A list of Third party plugins is available. These usually require Rust and Cargo package manager to be installed and also seem to run better on unix like OSs.
